y make it easy, and that's the key to quad kiting -- ease.<br><br>I suggest heading to Eastern Wastes as soon as you get (C)ircle (o)f (F)orce, CoF.  The walrus's are located in the southwest corner of EW, and you should quad them until you're through 35 when you can try ulthorks, or you can keep w/ walrus's until 38 then go to ulthorks.  Either way, here are the tips to a successful quad.<br><br>Activate your SoW _BEFORE_ you start your Quad, especially if you're using TBoots / SoW potions, preparation could save your life. ;-)  Go find yourself a nice target and run past and flux it (don't BoF yet)  Run it around, until you gather 4 total mobs (either by fluxxing or using the mobs aggro range to aggro more).<br><br>Run around them in circles so they bunch up together behind you, when you're satisfied with their bunching take off down the shore line (if you're in EW or any open space if you in some other zone)  Right click your SoTF until you get out of range message.  Stop and spam BoF until it starts casting.  If you don't snare all 4 first try don't worry ;-)  Start running away, retarget, and using the same tactics as before cast BoF on the unsnared mobs when you get the out of range message.  Once you get all the mobs snared, you'll have to rebunch them (if you didn't snare them all on try one).  The easiest way I've found is to have one bunch on either side of you about equal distances to either side, then just start walknig backwards and  they'll keep walking closer together.  If you misjudge it, just run them in circles to get them nice and bunched, then BoF again to get them all on the same timer.<br><br>Now the fun part, run away for about 5 seconds, stop, and CoF. *Rinse and Repeat*  You should be able to kill walrus's and ulthork hunters and coldain dwarves on one BoF timer.  The ulthork warriors sometimes take more than one.  BoF usually lasts for 7+ CoF, but if you want to be safe, re-BoF after 6 CoF's, this should keep any mobs from breaking your BoF at a bad time.<br><br>If you have to harvest mid kite (which i don't recommend, but sometimes it's necessary)  Make sure you have ample time left on your BoF and run away for like 10-12 seconds (you can count it out to youself, stop and Harvest.  When you're unstunned the mobs should just be entering the range of CoF, so you can continue kiting right away.  That easy =)<br><br><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>Suggested XP Ranges in EW</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--><br>34-40  -Walrus<br>36-43     -Ulthork Hunters<br>37-43     -Coldain Camps<br>38-44     -Ulthork Warriors<br><br>That's all there is to it,  happy Quading  (any feedback / suggestions welcome)<br><br>***NOTE:  I'm not saying this is necessarily the best or most effective method to quad kiting, quading in general is pretty straightforward for the most part, I'm merely outlining the method that I've found to work best for me.  =)<br><br>Stiffu Noob<br>Luclin <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table><table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm20.showPrevMessage?topicID=56.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm20.showNextMessage?topicID=56.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=56.topic><img src=http://www.graffe.com/messageboard/add_reply.gif border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm20.emailToFriend?topicID=56.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0 alt="Email This To a Friend"> Email This To a Friend</a><br> <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm20.threadControl?topicID=56.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/professional/deleteThread.gif bo